            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Sarah Jafari\u2019s life is a meticulously curated system, much like the restaurant operations she oversees. Raised in Sacramento by her Iranian father, a charismatic engineer who treated every family dinner like a feast, and her practical, American mother, an accountant, Sarah inherited a unique blend of warm hospitality and sharp business acumen. Her father\u2019s love for creating communal joy through food planted a seed, but it was the systematic chaos of restaurant kitchens, which she witnessed working as a hostess in college, that truly captivated her.\n\nForsaking a more traditional business path, she pursued a specialized MBA in Hospitality Management from Cornell. It was a pivotal decision that set her on a trajectory toward the upper echelons of the food world. Armed with her degree, she moved to San Francisco, drawn by its revolutionary culinary scene. She started as a general manager for a single high-end bistro, quickly earning a reputation for improving efficiency and staff morale without sacrificing quality. Her big break came when she was hired by a burgeoning restaurant group, where she climbed the ladder to her current role as Director of Operations.\n\nA key turning point was navigating the group through the pandemic, a brutal test of logistics and leadership that solidified her value and left her both exhausted and proud. That period also coincided with the amicable end of a long-term relationship, pushing her to pour her energy into her career.\n\nNow 42, Sarah lives in a modern apartment in Hayes Valley. Her 2.8-mile commute on the MUNI is a cherished ritual, a brief pocket of time to listen to a podcast before diving into a day of spreadsheets, vendor negotiations, and impromptu staff check-ins across the city. Her social life is intertwined with her work, consisting of industry events and dinners with a close circle of friends.\n\nThough fulfilled professionally, Sarah dreams of achieving a better balance. She envisions becoming an equity partner in the group while also carving out time for herself\u2014perhaps rediscovering her love for hiking in Marin or finally taking a pottery class. She hopes to find a partner who understands her ambition but also reminds her to savor the moments outside the relentless pace of her industry. San Francisco is no longer just a career destination; it\u2019s the backdrop for the next, more personal, chapter she is determined to write."
